Section Summary: Paolo Veronese, born Paolo Caliari in 1528 in Verona, was a great painter known for his unique blend of absurdity and adorability. He was trained by his uncle, Antonio Badile, and developed his skills in line drawing by copying the engravings of masters like Albert Durer. Veronese's early work was influenced by his time in Verona and his collaborations with his friend Battista Zelotti, with whom he decorated palaces in Tiene and Fanzolo. He eventually moved to Venice, a city that would become the inspiration for many of his works, and where he would develop his distinctive style characterized by vibrant colors and magnificent expression. Veronese's passion for Venice and his desire for glory drove his artistic career, earning him a reputation as one of the greatest painters of his time.
